      "text": "# Money and (The End Of) Violence"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cf5a405301cc1d26",
      "text": "While Knapp and the majority of today's \"neochartalists\" (Tcherneva 2006) are aware of the coercive character of money, more precisely of the fact that a monopolist of violence is able to impose the use of a certain means of payment, they nevertheless consider the political taxation competence of the state to be a necessity of the market economy, if not an economic location and socio-political blessing, David Graeber (2011) in his history of debt emphasizes the historical and structural connection between money and violence."
